			<title><![CDATA[[IT People] Need your suggestions! [Big Data]]]></title>
			<link>http://www.graffe.com/forums/showthread.php?75924-IT-People-Need-your-suggestions!-Big-Data&amp;goto=newpost</link>
			<pubDate>Sat, 12 Oct 2013 16:51:36 GMT</pubDate>
			<description>IT People! 
 
I am considering picking up some more IT skills. Suppose, hypothetically, that there is this guy named Istari.  He speaks Chinese and knows a thing or two about business in China.  One of the things that Istari occasionally gets asked to do is help determine whether Chinese...</description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<div>IT People!<br />
<br />
I am considering picking up some more IT skills. Suppose, hypothetically, that there is this guy named Istari.  He speaks Chinese and knows a thing or two about business in China.  One of the things that Istari occasionally gets asked to do is help determine whether Chinese subsidiaries of US-Owned corporations business operations are in compliance with SEC/DOJ requirements. I have had many wonderful adventures in China, from being kidnapped, interrogated by the communist party, poisoned repeatedly (great food, though), and there was that one time a toilet collapsed on top of me. But that's beside the point. So suppose someone knows about Chinese business practices and language, and also knows about what requirements apply to those businesses if you have a USA affiliate (i.e. a parent company or a subsidiary, must comply with various requirements for fair business competition practices)<br />
<br />
So here's the question for IT Folks. There is a whole lot of electronically stored information these days being kept by companies, especially in China, where the country is basically dominated by introverted internet nerds.  The international trade compliance people can't really keep up with it, since that would basically involve looking at millions of pages of highly vaguely worded stuff, and the local Chinese dudes are pretty clubby anyway.   So usually the only time this gets looked into is during an internal investigation, which is exorbitantly expensive to conduct. This would involve lots of predictive analytics of natural language documents.<br />
<br />
That's changing with Big Data and such, and this is an evolving area that I'm interested in looking into.  Basically, with predictive analytics, a person familiar with the Chinese linguistic set and the United States trade requirements would be able to teach a computer how to read, say, 10,000,000 pages of electronic information and spit out a concise data set pointing at foreign business practices inconsistent with the parent company's corporate policies. I could then look at the set, and prepare to kick some butt. What I need to figure out is: how can I learn this snazz? I know there's going to be several years before this sort of technology takes off in this particular sector. It looks to me like this would be some sort of computer science/info systems, or digital forensics / predictive forensics type learning. I figure we have several years before this really takes off; it's only in 2013 that there's been talk of startups experimenting with this sort of thing.<br />
<br />
I was looking around at some master's programs to pick up a credential, but also take some time to teach myself. I've looked at a few programs, like M.S. in any of: computer science (machine learning), computer information systems, and business analytics. I'd probably do these part-time over several years while working. The business analytics programs seemed relevant, since I'm not looking to be an engineer so much as do information analysis.<br />
<br />
In short, what tech skills would I need to do this trick of combining my business/linguistic knowledge into analytics effectively?</div>

