			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<div>As a kid, I took vitamin C whenever my mother handed me one, and I occasionally ate my Flinstone's vitamins if I remembered to ask my mother for one. Every morning I'd watch my father get up at the butt crack of dawn, and take a Centrum Silver, and a glass of metamucil, and then head out to the gym. <br />
<br />
Since I've become an adult, whenever I feel a cold coming on, I take a couple doses of Airborne, or Emergen-C; whichever seems to be available wherever I stop to get it. <br />
<br />
But I've never truly been very regular about taking multi-vitamins, myself. Just sort of as an imaginary preventative measure against getting sick. <br />
<br />
My google-fu has resulted in very little to support the use of multi-viatmins without trying to sell me some in addition to the ones they review. Most articles seem to state that there are few physicians who have seen any data to conclude that multi-vitamins will help prevent heart disease, or anything else someone would prefer not to suffer in their mid to late life. <br />
<br />
